406→                           A problem of Erdős and Szekeres, who observed that\[\textrm{gcd}\left( \binom{n}{i},\binom{n}{j}\right) \geq \frac{\binom{n}{i}}{\binom{j}{i}}\geq 2^i\](in particular the greatest common divisor is always $&gt;1$). This inequality is sharp for $i=1$, $j=p$, and $n=2p$.<br><br>This was resolved by Bergman <a href="#cite-Be11-698" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Be11','698'); return false;">[Be11]</a>, who proved that for any $2\leq i&lt;j\leq n/2$\[\textrm{gcd}\left( \binom{n}{i},\binom{n}{j}\right) \gg n^{1/2}\frac{2^i}{i^{3/2}},\]where the implied constant is absolute.
